1
00:00:04,481 --> 00:00:06,201
- Are we done?
- Listen, I--

2
00:00:06,399 --> 00:00:10,491
This attack on my brother-in-law,
I don't know what it means.

3
00:00:10,695 --> 00:00:12,450
Please.

4
00:00:13,405 --> 00:00:15,873
I fear for my family.

5
00:00:16,199 --> 00:00:18,584
I'm sure they'll be fine.

6
00:00:19,077 --> 00:00:22,588
I'm told the assassin that survived
is gravely injured.

7
00:00:22,788 --> 00:00:24,793
It's doubtful he'll live.

8
00:00:25,583 --> 00:00:28,679
Now, thank me and shake my hand.

9
00:00:30,837 --> 00:00:35,178
- Thank you. Thank you again.
- You're quite welcome, Mr. White.

10
00:00:36,092 --> 00:00:38,227
Guys, guys, hurry up.

11
00:00:38,427 --> 00:00:41,392
- Can we go now?
- Upstairs, come on.

12
00:00:42,347 --> 00:00:44,103
What's happening?

13
00:00:44,849 --> 00:00:46,106
Eight forty-three.

14
00:00:46,309 --> 00:00:49,487
Time of death, 20:43.

15
00:00:50,521 --> 00:00:52,822
Burn in hell, you piece of shit.

16
00:00:59,403 --> 00:01:01,622
One of the gunmen died
at the scene.

17
00:01:01,822 --> 00:01:05,036
The second succumbed to his wounds
earlier this evening.

18
00:01:05,242 --> 00:01:06,878
Agents with the DEA and FBI...

19
00:01:07,077 --> 00:01:11,003
...in conjunction with APD are working
with Mexican law enforcement...

20
00:01:11,205 --> 00:01:15,084
...in an attempt to identify
the deceased suspects. Both--

21
00:01:32,849 --> 00:01:35,150
I can give you the highlights.

22
00:01:36,060 --> 00:01:38,029
Your nephews grew impatient.

23
00:01:38,228 --> 00:01:41,822
They continued to press me
for my permission to kill Walter White.

24
00:01:42,023 --> 00:01:46,662
When I wouldn't give it, they settled
instead for DEA Agent Schrader.

25
00:01:47,737 --> 00:01:49,741
But a phone call was placed...

26
00:01:49,947 --> 00:01:52,627
...to Agent Schrader
moments before the attack.

27
00:01:52,824 --> 00:01:55,374
Thus giving him the upper hand.

28
00:01:55,577 --> 00:01:58,542
Marco was shot in the face
and died instantly.

29
00:01:58,746 --> 00:02:01,795
Leonel lingered for several hours.

30
00:02:03,041 --> 00:02:05,841
The warning call to the DEA agent...

31
00:02:06,753 --> 00:02:09,718
...Juan Bolsa
may have some insight...

32
00:02:09,922 --> 00:02:12,010
...into who placed it.

33
00:02:12,216 --> 00:02:14,435
Yesterday,
federales raided his hacienda.

34
00:02:14,635 --> 00:02:17,683
And in the confusion,
Juan was shot dead.

35
00:02:18,221 --> 00:02:20,522
An accident, perhaps.

36
00:02:21,057 --> 00:02:24,271
A mistake made by his own men.

37
00:02:24,894 --> 00:02:26,945
Though we may never know.

38
00:02:27,688 --> 00:02:30,819
At any rate,
I thought you should hear it from me.

39
00:02:40,449 --> 00:02:44,671
This is what comes
of blood for blood, Hector.

40
00:03:37,665 --> 00:03:39,800
So is this the loud one?

41
00:03:42,252 --> 00:03:43,462
What?

42
00:03:49,967 --> 00:03:52,600
No. This is the PET/CT scan.

43
00:03:52,803 --> 00:03:56,148
Positron emission tomography.

44
00:03:57,932 --> 00:04:04,907
They've paired that
with computed x-ray tomography.

45
00:04:06,648 --> 00:04:09,233
Quiet. No magnets.

46
00:04:09,484 --> 00:04:11,239
Right, okay.

47
00:04:11,444 --> 00:04:12,701
Yeah, thanks.

48
00:04:14,655 --> 00:04:16,576
I'm still pretty new at this.

49
00:04:17,032 --> 00:04:19,250
One minute,
I'm starting a new business...

50
00:04:19,451 --> 00:04:21,621
...my wife and I
are thinking about kids.

51
00:04:21,828 --> 00:04:24,413
Walk into a doctor's office
and suddenly ...

52
00:04:24,622 --> 00:04:27,919
- I mean, life as I know it--
- Excuse me.

53
00:04:28,583 --> 00:04:31,548
Yes. I'm waiting
to hear a progress report...

54
00:04:31,753 --> 00:04:35,430
...on the thing we discussed,
so call me.

55
00:04:39,176 --> 00:04:42,473
Anyway, so for me,
that's been the biggest wake-up call.

56
00:04:42,679 --> 00:04:45,608
Letting go, giving up control.

57
00:04:45,807 --> 00:04:49,816
You know, it's like they say,
"Man plans and God laughs."

58
00:04:50,519 --> 00:04:54,778
That is such bullshit.

59
00:04:55,273 --> 00:04:56,530
Excuse me?

60
00:04:56,733 --> 00:04:59,236
Never give up control.

61
00:05:00,277 --> 00:05:03,207
Live life on your own terms.

62
00:05:03,989 --> 00:05:06,457
Yeah, no,
I get what you're saying...

63
00:05:06,658 --> 00:05:08,793
...but cancer is cancer, so...

64
00:05:08,993 --> 00:05:10,998
To hell with your cancer.

65
00:05:11,454 --> 00:05:14,253
I've been living with cancer
for the better part of a year.

66
00:05:14,456 --> 00:05:18,336
From the start, it's a death sentence.
That's what they keep telling me.

67
00:05:18,543 --> 00:05:20,215
Well, guess what?

68
00:05:20,420 --> 00:05:23,717
Every life comes
with a death sentence.

69
00:05:23,923 --> 00:05:28,264
So every few months,
I come in here for my regular scan...

70
00:05:28,468 --> 00:05:32,311
...knowing full well
that one of these times--

71
00:05:32,513 --> 00:05:34,898
Hell, maybe even today.

72
00:05:36,142 --> 00:05:38,775
--I'm gonna hear some bad news.

73
00:05:39,019 --> 00:05:40,940
But until then...

74
00:05:41,521 --> 00:05:43,241
...who's in charge?

75
00:05:43,648 --> 00:05:45,119
Me.

76
00:05:47,902 --> 00:05:50,238
That's how I live my life.

77
00:06:07,919 --> 00:06:10,849
This residue here is why we descale
with cool water...

78
00:06:11,047 --> 00:06:13,550
...from the walk-in
and not water from the tap.

79
00:06:13,757 --> 00:06:15,596
Do it again, please.

80
00:06:18,511 --> 00:06:21,857
Pollos Hermanos, where something
delicious is always cooking.

81
00:06:23,349 --> 00:06:25,235
Yes, detective.

82
00:06:49,663 --> 00:06:50,874
Yeah.

83
00:06:52,707 --> 00:06:54,759
- Gustavo, thanks for coming.
- Pleasure.

84
00:06:54,959 --> 00:06:57,463
- How's Kathi?
- Much better, thank you.

85
00:06:57,670 --> 00:07:00,351
- And you know Hank Schrader?
- Yes, indeed.

86
00:07:00,548 --> 00:07:02,967
- And Steve Gomez?
- How was your meal?

87
00:07:03,175 --> 00:07:06,389
Agent Schrader and I had a chance
to catch up at one of my restaurants.

88
00:07:06,594 --> 00:07:09,940
I'd eat there every day
but I wouldn't fit through the door.

89
00:07:10,181 --> 00:07:12,150
- Well, should we get started?
- Yeah.

90
00:07:13,851 --> 00:07:17,232
- I'd like to record this conversation.
- Of course.

91
00:07:21,399 --> 00:07:26,785
The DEA is working on an investigation
which may overlap with my own...

92
00:07:26,987 --> 00:07:28,707
...so I've asked them to sit in.

93
00:07:28,905 --> 00:07:32,536
Gus, we all appreciate your coming
in here to talk to us...

94
00:07:32,742 --> 00:07:35,625
...but you have the right
to have an attorney present.

95
00:07:35,828 --> 00:07:39,042
Oh, well, I can't see
how that would be necessary.

96
00:07:39,248 --> 00:07:41,252
But then,
I have no idea why I'm here.

97
00:07:41,458 --> 00:07:43,048
So you wish to continue?

98
00:07:43,251 --> 00:07:47,972
Please. I'm very anxious
to find out what this is all about.

99
00:07:48,214 --> 00:07:51,807
Sir, your fingerprints were found
at a crime scene.

100
00:07:52,259 --> 00:07:55,272
Really? That's surprising.

101
00:07:55,470 --> 00:07:58,103
A drug-related homicide.

102
00:08:03,769 --> 00:08:06,449
Gale Boetticher's apartment.

103
00:08:10,608 --> 00:08:12,280
So you knew the victim?

104
00:08:17,072 --> 00:08:21,627
Fifteen years ago, I established
a chemistry scholarship at UNM.

105
00:08:21,826 --> 00:08:24,506
I named it
after Maximino Arciniega...

106
00:08:24,703 --> 00:08:26,839
...a dear friend of mine
who died young.

107
00:08:27,164 --> 00:08:29,584
Gale was a recipient
of this scholarship.

108
00:08:29,791 --> 00:08:33,931
He was perhaps one of three dozen.

109
00:08:34,128 --> 00:08:35,848
I see.

110
00:08:36,505 --> 00:08:40,562
And Mr. Boetticher graduated in ...

111
00:08:40,759 --> 00:08:43,558
-1999.
- That sounds right.

112
00:08:43,761 --> 00:08:46,691
And you kept in contact with him
over all this time?

113
00:08:46,889 --> 00:08:51,444
Oh, no. I hadn't seen Gale for years
until I ran into him a few weeks ago.

114
00:08:51,643 --> 00:08:54,656
- Ran into him where?
- At the restaurant.

115
00:08:55,563 --> 00:08:58,612
Well, "ran into" isn't quite accurate,
as I assumed...

116
00:08:58,816 --> 00:09:02,778
...he came by to re-establish contact
with me. We caught up briefly.

117
00:09:02,986 --> 00:09:06,699
He invited me to dinner
the following night and I accepted.

118
00:09:08,199 --> 00:09:12,256
It was perhaps a week later
when I read about him in the paper.

119
00:09:12,453 --> 00:09:15,252
- Drug related, you said?
-It's a good possibility.

120
00:09:15,455 --> 00:09:17,709
The paper made no mention of that.

121
00:09:17,916 --> 00:09:20,596
I assumed
that it was a random crime.

122
00:09:20,793 --> 00:09:24,969
So after years with no contact,
he shows up in your restaurant...

123
00:09:25,172 --> 00:09:28,518
...and invites you to dinner?
- He wanted money.

124
00:09:28,717 --> 00:09:31,646
- Gale Boetticher asked for money?
- He didn't say that.

125
00:09:32,011 --> 00:09:36,767
He spoke in terms
of a vague investment opportunity.

126
00:09:36,974 --> 00:09:40,984
But it was my suspicion, yes,
as to why he invited me into his home.

127
00:09:41,186 --> 00:09:46,488
He was a very, very talented chemist,
but for reasons I never understood...

128
00:09:46,691 --> 00:09:49,739
...he was more interested
in taking shortcuts...

129
00:09:49,943 --> 00:09:53,656
...than what would or could have been
a very promising career.

130
00:09:53,863 --> 00:09:55,999
Personal shortcomings
notwithstanding...

131
00:09:56,199 --> 00:09:58,369
...he was a warm, gentle person...

132
00:09:58,576 --> 00:10:00,960
...and I thought a lot of him.

133
00:10:02,996 --> 00:10:07,136
At any rate,
I declined his business offer...

134
00:10:07,333 --> 00:10:10,679
...and after
what was a very pleasant meal, left.

135
00:10:11,253 --> 00:10:13,056
Can you tell us where you were...

136
00:10:13,255 --> 00:10:16,849
...on the night of Wednesday the 23rd
at around 8 p.m.?

137
00:10:17,050 --> 00:10:21,724
- Not an accusation, just a question.
- No, I understand. Let's see.

138
00:10:23,889 --> 00:10:25,526
Twenty-third.

139
00:10:26,850 --> 00:10:29,567
I was at a fundraiser
at Presbyterian Hospital.

140
00:10:29,769 --> 00:10:32,450
I was there from 7 to about 10.

141
00:10:36,817 --> 00:10:38,739
Anyone else?

142
00:10:41,780 --> 00:10:44,544
Sorry, yeah. Just one other thing.

143
00:10:45,032 --> 00:10:47,618
Is Gustavo Fring your real name?

144
00:10:49,870 --> 00:10:51,626
Is it my real name?

145
00:10:51,830 --> 00:10:55,507
I know you're a Chilean national...

146
00:10:55,708 --> 00:10:58,887
...but there are no records of you
ever living there.

147
00:10:59,587 --> 00:11:01,093
Really?

148
00:11:01,422 --> 00:11:06,095
I mean, records show that you
immigrated to Mexico in 1986...

149
00:11:06,301 --> 00:11:10,690
...and years later, you were granted
an entry visa to the United States.

150
00:11:10,888 --> 00:11:16,938
But there's no record of Gustavo Fring
ever having existed in Chile...

151
00:11:17,143 --> 00:11:20,156
...which I find, I don't know, strange.

152
00:11:20,646 --> 00:11:22,734
Well, no, really, it isn't.

153
00:11:23,274 --> 00:11:25,991
Pinochet's government
was guilty of many sins.

154
00:11:26,193 --> 00:11:28,529
First and foremost
were human rights abuses.

155
00:11:29,070 --> 00:11:32,617
But it was also notoriously unreliable
at keeping records.

156
00:11:33,908 --> 00:11:36,838
I'm sure if you keep digging,
you'll find me.

157
00:11:39,746 --> 00:11:42,296
Okay, I think that's it, Gus.
Thank you.

158
00:11:42,499 --> 00:11:45,049
I hope that I was of some small help.

159
00:11:45,251 --> 00:11:48,798
- You were, absolutely. Thank you.
- You're very welcome.

160
00:11:49,004 --> 00:11:50,641
Good to see you again. Oh, no.

161
00:11:50,839 --> 00:11:53,307
- No, please, please. Don't get up.
- Thanks.

162
00:11:58,596 --> 00:12:00,186
Gentlemen.

163
00:12:22,617 --> 00:12:24,835
So are we buying?

164
00:12:25,035 --> 00:12:27,336
This thing with his name?
What are you thinking?

165
00:12:27,537 --> 00:12:30,634
Sure, the record-keeping
in South America's hit or miss.

166
00:12:30,832 --> 00:12:33,300
I mean, we run into that all the time,
right?

167
00:12:33,501 --> 00:12:37,213
But we usually find something.
Before '86 this guy's a ghost.

168
00:12:37,421 --> 00:12:41,431
If State Department wasn't satisfied,
they wouldn't have naturalized him.

169
00:12:41,633 --> 00:12:45,096
Well, maybe,
but he emigrated from Mexico in '89.

170
00:12:45,303 --> 00:12:48,600
State just wasn't as tough
on background checks pre-9/11.

171
00:12:48,806 --> 00:12:52,020
I don't know what this has to do
with the case at hand.

172
00:12:52,225 --> 00:12:55,986
I was curious when his print showed up
at Boetticher's apartment.

173
00:12:56,187 --> 00:12:58,239
For me, the scholarship explains it.

174
00:12:58,439 --> 00:13:00,693
I'll admit to a certain degree of bias.

175
00:13:00,899 --> 00:13:03,829
This man has been a longtime friend
of DEA.

176
00:13:04,027 --> 00:13:08,950
But that being said,
I thought his story was credible.

177
00:13:09,365 --> 00:13:11,915
Well, I agree.
I think it was a good story.

178
00:13:12,117 --> 00:13:14,288
Still, why are we hearing it now?

179
00:13:14,495 --> 00:13:15,503
What do you mean?

180
00:13:15,704 --> 00:13:20,342
Well, like you said, he's a-- This man
is a big law enforcement booster.

181
00:13:20,541 --> 00:13:24,337
He's reading the newspaper and sees
that someone he had dinner with...

182
00:13:24,545 --> 00:13:27,130
...someone he thought a lot of
was murdered.

183
00:13:27,339 --> 00:13:30,138
He reads this
and he doesn't make a phone call?

184
00:13:30,592 --> 00:13:34,732
Didn't call you
or one of his other cop friends...

185
00:13:34,929 --> 00:13:38,855
...to share his connection with the case
or ask about the investigation?

186
00:13:39,057 --> 00:13:42,154
We can't predicate
a criminal investigation...

187
00:13:42,352 --> 00:13:44,487
...on a person
not making phone calls.

188
00:13:46,314 --> 00:13:47,950
What do you think, Tim?

189
00:13:48,148 --> 00:13:51,991
Well, I wanna follow up
on the scholarship, the alibi...

190
00:13:52,194 --> 00:13:54,163
...but my overall impression?

191
00:13:54,362 --> 00:13:55,536
I believed him.

192
00:14:05,789 --> 00:14:09,300
Nice touch. Birdbath.

193
00:14:10,584 --> 00:14:13,265
- Hey, tiger, how's it hanging?
- Good.

194
00:14:15,213 --> 00:14:18,262
Yeah, so very nice.

195
00:14:18,466 --> 00:14:20,601
What's the damage?

196
00:14:20,968 --> 00:14:23,816
Twelve hundred a month.
I did a lot of research.

197
00:14:24,013 --> 00:14:27,643
- That's a pretty good deal.
- You kidding me? That's a great deal.

198
00:14:27,849 --> 00:14:29,735
Speaking of which...

199
00:14:30,226 --> 00:14:32,148
...that's for the week.

200
00:14:32,353 --> 00:14:36,149
Plus there's a little extra in there
for any move-related incidentals.

201
00:14:36,357 --> 00:14:37,400
Thank you.

202
00:14:38,066 --> 00:14:40,996
- Hey, champ, how's the new school?
- Good.

203
00:14:41,194 --> 00:14:43,116
I loved school when I was your age.

204
00:14:43,321 --> 00:14:46,951
Seesaws, story time,
chasing girls with sticks.

205
00:14:56,791 --> 00:15:01,429
It wasn't until the fifth grade
that I found out she liked me too...

206
00:15:01,837 --> 00:15:05,550
...but by then her family had moved
to Scottsdale, so ...

207
00:15:07,884 --> 00:15:10,185
- Carpe diem, okay?
- Okay.

208
00:15:10,386 --> 00:15:11,892
All right. Good boy.

209
00:15:13,055 --> 00:15:16,436
So you'll thank Jesse again
from both of us?

210
00:15:16,641 --> 00:15:17,982
You got it.

211
00:15:19,477 --> 00:15:22,858
- So is he-- How's he doing?
- Jesse?

212
00:15:28,443 --> 00:15:33,164
He's good. He's busy.

213
00:15:41,621 --> 00:15:42,962
How is it?

214
00:15:43,164 --> 00:15:48,004
Space, lots of light. it's--
Little garden outback. it's nice.

215
00:15:49,086 --> 00:15:52,467
And Brock? How's he doing?

216
00:15:52,923 --> 00:15:56,054
Hey, look, I don't mind
dropping checks off every week...

217
00:15:56,259 --> 00:15:57,682
...like Ed McMahon...

218
00:15:57,885 --> 00:16:00,270
...but if you wanna know
how they're doing...

219
00:16:00,471 --> 00:16:03,235
...why don't you go see for yourself?

220
00:16:08,227 --> 00:16:09,615
I'll catch you later.

221
00:16:11,022 --> 00:16:13,607
- Hey, you gonna need a ride home?
- No.

222
00:16:58,979 --> 00:17:00,320
Great.

223
00:17:04,568 --> 00:17:07,285
Anyway,
I'm proud for not losing my cool.

224
00:17:07,487 --> 00:17:10,334
Plus, it shows our crew
that I will support them...

225
00:17:10,531 --> 00:17:12,370
...if a customer's being rude.

226
00:17:12,574 --> 00:17:16,002
You're really taking to this whole
be-your-own-boss thing.

227
00:17:16,495 --> 00:17:19,673
Yeah. I guess I am.

228
00:17:20,164 --> 00:17:21,920
Actually...

229
00:17:22,625 --> 00:17:26,136
...I'm thinking about making the move
up to management.

230
00:17:26,336 --> 00:17:28,222
Jesus. Corporate America, look out.

231
00:17:28,421 --> 00:17:31,102
Excuse me,
I would be a vast improvement.

232
00:17:31,299 --> 00:17:35,225
No one in Kleinman's entire front office
knows about giving an x-ray...

233
00:17:35,428 --> 00:17:37,064
...which is just...

234
00:17:37,471 --> 00:17:40,188
Hey, Dad, whatever happened
with your scan?

235
00:17:40,390 --> 00:17:42,477
Did you get the results back?

236
00:17:43,476 --> 00:17:46,857
Yeah, I did...

237
00:17:47,063 --> 00:17:49,233
...and I'm still in remission.

238
00:17:49,440 --> 00:17:53,948
So you're all gonna have to be stuck
with me for a while longer.

239
00:17:54,152 --> 00:17:55,196
Cheers, buddy.

240
00:17:57,613 --> 00:18:00,294
What about you, Hank?
How you feeling these days?

241
00:18:00,491 --> 00:18:02,496
You know, getting there.

242
00:18:02,701 --> 00:18:07,209
The other day, he had a big powwow
with all the DEA muckety-mucks.

243
00:18:08,122 --> 00:18:09,878
What was that about?

244
00:18:10,333 --> 00:18:13,132
